[Lumpy skin disease (LSD), caused by a capripox viral disease of cattle, is an OIE-notifiable disease that has spread from Africa to the Middle East and, in recent years, into southeast Europe and southwest Asia, continuing northeastwards as far as Kazakhstan and adjacent Russian territories (see OIE's global outbreaks map, since 2014, at https://tinyurl.com/yaemejby). LSD is not zoonotic.

According to Oman's periodic reports to the OIE, the disease is endemic. During 2017, 90 outbreaks were reported, including 325 cases and 9 deaths. No vaccination applied.

Bovine ephemeral fever (BEF, also known as "3-day sickness"), is an economically important arboviral disease that affects cattle and water buffalo and is widespread in tropical and semitropical areas of the eastern hemisphere. In most cases, the main impact is on productivity. While the illness is usually brief, it can result in decreased milk yield, loss of condition, and reproductive losses, and recovery can be prolonged in some animals. Mortality is typically low (1-2 percent); however, significantly higher case-fatality rates were reported in some recent outbreaks.

BEF is caused by bovine ephemeral fever virus (BEFV), a member of the genus _Ephemerovirus_ in the family Rhabdoviridae. It is not included in OIE's list, and its occurrence does not require notification. However, when diagnosed for the 1st time in non-endemic countries, such a new introduction may be followed by reporting to the OIE (e.g., Tajikistan, 2002; see archive no. 20020814.5055). The disease is not zoonotic.

BEF, which has a seasonal pattern, has recently been reported from another Middle-Eastern country, Israel, and has, most probably, been circulating in other countries in the region. - Mod.AS

